}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48473"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother with a two-day history of right ear pain and discharge. He has been swimming at the local pool every day this week. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a temperature of 37.1\u00b0C, pulse rate 88/min, respiratory rate 16/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, and SpO2 99% on room air. Otoscopy of the right ear reveals an erythematous, swollen external auditory canal with purulent discharge. The tympanic membrane is difficult to visualise. The left ear appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute otitis media","Acute mastoiditis","Acute otitis externa","Chronic suppurative otitis media","Foreign body"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of otalgia, otorrhoea, and tenderness of the external auditory canal is consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute otitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E. The history of recent swimming is a risk factor, as moisture in the ear canal can lead to maceration of the skin and predispose to infection. \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E are the most common causative organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with otalgia, fever, and hearing loss. The tympanic membrane would appear erythematous and bulging on otoscopy, rather than the canal inflammation seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute mastoiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is a complication of untreated acute otitis media. It presents with postauricular erythema, swelling, and tenderness, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic suppurative otitis media\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a persistent discharge from the middle ear through a perforated tympanic membrane. The duration is longer than the acute presentation described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eforeign body\u003C/strong\u003E in the ear canal can cause otalgia and otorrhoea, but there are no specific features to suggest this on examination. The diffuse canal inflammation is more consistent with infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute otitis externa presents with otalgia, otorrhoea, and tenderness of the external auditory canal.","Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Staphylococcus aureus are the most common causative organisms in acute otitis externa."],"references":["Goguen LA. External otitis:  Pathogenesis, clinical features, and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/external-otitis-pathogenesis-clinical-features-and-diagnosis?topicRef=16516\u0026source=see_link","Cheffins T, Heal C, Rudolphy S. Acute otitis externa: management by GPs in North Queensland. Aust Fam Physician. 2009;38(4):262-3, 265-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19350078/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-12T15:52:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T15:58:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6366"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48473"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attrib